{"cursor":"6906","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n awarded Panchen Lama the Guarding the National Master]] 'Thubten Choekyi Nyima'\n () (1883 – 1937), often referred to as Choekyi Nyima, was the 9th Panchen\n Lama of Tibet.\n\nIn 1901, Choekyi Nyima was visited by the Mongolian Lama, Agvan Dorzhiev.\nAlthough he only stayed for two days at Tashilhunpo, Dorzhiev received some\nsecret teachings from the Panchen Lama, as well as readings of the Prayer of\nShambhala, written by Lobsang Palden Yeshe, the sixth (or third) Panchen Lama,\nconcerning the Buddhist kingdom of Shambhala, which were of great importance to\nDorzhiev's developing understanding of the Kalachakra ('Wheel of Time') tantric\nteachings. Choekyi Nyima also gave Dorzhiev gifts including some golden\nstatues. Snelling 1993, pg. 77\n\nIn 1906, Sir Charles Alfred Bell, was invited to visit the 9th Panchen Lama at\nTashilhunpo, where they had friendly discussions on the political\nsituation. Chapman 1940, pg. 141\n\nHe fled to Inner Mongolia, China in 1924 after a dispute with the thirteenth\nDalai Lama when he sensed that he might face threat after his own monasteryâs\nmonks were prohibited from holding any office in the Central Tibetan government\nand his officials were locked up in Lhasa. Tuttle 2006 The Dalai Lama\nwas attempting to collect revenue from the Panchen Lama's estate to cover a\nfourth of Tibet's military expenses, and to reduce the power of the Panchen\nLama, who at the time enjoyed rule over an effectively autonomous region around\nShigatse. Powers 2004, pg. 99\n\nIn China, the ninth Panchen Lama worked on plans to develop Tibet along modern\nlines. Jagou, pp. 156-159, 206-208 He also held a position in the\nMongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission.\n\nAccording to Chinese sources, the Panchen Lama was considered extremely \"pro\nChinese\".\n\nChoekyi adopted the ideas of Sun Yatsen like the Kham revolutionary Pandatsang\nRapga. It has been suggested he read the works of Sun Yatsen which\nwere translated by Rapga.\n\nIn 1937, he died in GyÃªgu (Tibetan: Jyekundo; Chinese: Yushu) in Qinghai\nProvince.\n\nThe tombs of the fifth through the ninth Panchen Lamas were destroyed during the\nCultural Revolution and have been rebuilt by the tenth Panchen Lama with a huge\ntomb at Tashilhunpo Monastery in Shigatse, known as the Tashi\nLangyar. Mayhew 2005, pg. 175.\n","linknr":285,"url":"Thubten_Chökyi_Nyima","recorded":1375054441,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Thubten_Choekyi_Nyima,_9th_Panchen_Lama&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Thubten_Choekyi_Nyima,_9th_Panchen_Lama&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Thubten_Choekyi_Nyima,_9th_Panchen_Lama","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Thubten_Ch%C3%B6kyi_Nyima&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:9thPanchen.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/9thPanchen.jpg/220px-9thPanchen.jpg","/wiki/File:9thPanchen.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf11/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Category:Tibetan_Buddhism","/wiki/Tibetan_Buddhism","/wiki/File:Faith_Buddhism_Vajra.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Faith_Buddhism_Vajra.svg/100px-Faith_Buddhism_Vajra.svg.png","/wiki/Schools_of_Buddhism","/wi